{"title_page": "Agust\u00ed Villaronga", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|Villaronga|Riutort}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Agust\u00edVillaronga.jpg\n| name         = Agust\u00ed Villaronga\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|03|04}}\n| birth_place  = [[Majorca]], Spain\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Film director, screenwriter, actor\n| yearsactive  = 1976\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Agust\u00ed Villaronga Riutort''' ({{IPA-ca|\u0259\u0263us\u02c8ti \u03b2i\u028e\u0259\u02c8\u027eo\u014b\u0261\u0259}}; born 4 March 1953)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/personne/fichepersonne_gen_cpersonne=202979.html|title=Agust\u00ed Villaronga|website=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|access-date=2 March 2016|language=fr}}</ref> is a Balearic Spanish [[film director]], [[screenwriter]] and actor.<ref name=\"spainisculture\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spainisculture.com/en/artistas_creadores/agusti_villaronga.html |title=Agust\u00ed Villaronga |accessdate=18 November 2011 |work=spainisculture}}</ref> He has directed seven feature films, a documentary, three projects for television and three shorts. His film ''[[Moon Child (1989 film)|El ni\u00f1o de la luna]]'' was entered into the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/237/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Moon Child |accessdate=1 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 he won the [[Goya Award for Best Director]] for ''[[Black Bread|Pa negre (Black Bread)]]''. The film was selected as the Spanish entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[84th Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"84th\">{{cite web |url=http://premiososcar2012.blogspot.com/2011/09/pa-negre-representara-espana-en-los.html |title=\"PA NEGRE\" REPRESENTAR\u00c1 A ESPA\u00d1A EN LOS OSCAR |accessdate=28 September 2011|work=CBC}}</ref> but it did not make the final shortlist.<ref name=\"Oscar Shortlist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2012/20120118.html |title=9 Foreign Language Films Vie for Oscar |accessdate=19 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67p5yGZlK?url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2012/20120118.html |archivedate=21 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nAgust\u00ed Villaronga was born on 4 March 1953 in [[Palma de Mallorca]], his grandparents had been itinerant puppeteers and his father was a child of the [[Spanish Civil War]], a fact that would resurface repeatedly in the director's filmography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2012/01/the-secret-of-black-bread-170412|title=The Secret of ''Black Bread''|last=Levine|first=Sydney|date=11 January 2012|website=[[IndieWire]]|access-date=7 July 2016|quote=Nor was [''Black Bread''] Villaronga's first film about children in the post Spanish Civil War era. [''The Sea''], ''In a Glass Cage'' and [''Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino''] all spoke of the consequences of the war, the perversions of war which changes the nautre of human beings, now, after, in the future and before. The perversions of war most interests Villaronga.}}</ref> Since childhood, his father encouraged his love for films and from early in his life he wanted to become a film director. He worked as an actor and made some shorts.\n\nVillaronga made his directorial debut in 1986 with the film ''[[Tras el cristal]]'', which was selected by the [[Berlin film festival]] receiving critical praise and many awards. The plot follows a former Nazi doctor, now paralyzed and depending on an iron lung to live, who begins to be taken care of by a young man, one of the children he abused during the war.\n''Tras el cristal'' already shows some of the key elements in Villaronga's filmography: a disturbed childhood marked by violence an early discovery of sexuality.\n\nHis second film, ''[[Moon Child (1989 film)|El ni\u00f1o de la Luna]]'' (1989), is about a child who goes to Africa to join a tribe awaiting the arrival of white child God. In 1992 he made a documentary, ''Al Andaluz'', produced by Segetel and the [[MoMa]] of [[New York city]]. For some years Villaronga tried unsuccessfully to find financing to adapt a novel by [[Merc\u00e8 Rodoreda]], ''Muerte en Primavera''. Instead he had to take some commission works. One of these was ''El pasajero clandestino'', a made for television project that lacked the personal characteristics of his filmography.\n\nCalled by actress [[Mar\u00eda Barranco]], Villaronga directed ''99.99'' a horror film more in synch with his themes, and that won some awards in festivals specialized in fantastic cinema. In 2000, Villaronga came back with a project of his own: ''[[The Sea (2000 film)|El mar]]'', a story set in [[Mallorca]] about three former childhood friends, traumatized by the violence they experienced during the Spanish civil war, that are reunited ten years later as young adults in a sanitary of tubercular patiences. The key elements in Villaronga's filmography are present in this story: childhood, sexual awakening, homosexuality and violence.\n\nIn 2002, Villaronga  co-directed with [[Lydia Zimmermann]] and [[Lydia Zimmermann#Isaac Pierre Racine|Isaac Pierre Racine]] the film ''[[Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino|En la mente del asesino]]''. In 2005 he directed a music video for French superstar [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]]'s song ''[[Fuck Them All]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mylene.net/mylene/c_fuck-them-all.php|title=Mylene.Net - Le site r\u00e9f\u00e9rence sur Myl\u00e8ne Farmer|author =Julien AUTIER|author2 =Philippe LEZE|author3 =Guillaume DATEZ|author4 =Sarah HOFER|last-author-amp =yes|work=mylene.net|accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> In 2007 he made ''Despu\u00e9s de la lluvia'', a made for television project adapting a stage play. It was only until 2010 with ''Pa negre'', when Villaronga finally achieved wider appeal. This film, winner of nine [[Goya Award]] including best film and best director, tells the story of an elven year old boy who growing up in the harsh period of the aftermath of the Spanish Civil War in [[Catalonia]]'s countryside discovers the world of lies around him.\n\nVillaronga followed ''P\u00e1 negre'''s success with  ''A Letter to Evita'', a TV miniseries co-produced by TV3, which recounts a real episode in the life of [[Eva Per\u00f3n]] while visiting [[Spain]] in the late 1940s.\n\nVillaronga is openly gay.<ref name=\"The Advocate, 11 April 2000, p. 46\">{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IGMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46 |title=Darkness in Berlin|accessdate=20 January 2013|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=11 April 2000|page=46}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography as director==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 99%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n!width=\"5%\"|Year\n!width=\"20%\"|English title\n!width=\"35%\"|Original title\n!width=\"40%\"|Notes\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Tras el cristal|In a Glass Cage]]''\n| ''Tras el cristal'' \n| Manfred Salzberg Award at the [[Berlin film festival]]\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1989\n| ''[[Moon Child (1989 film)|Moon Child]]''\n| ''El ni\u00f1o de la luna''\n| \n|-\n| 1992\n| ''Al-Andalus: The Art of Islamic Spain''\n| ''Al-Andalus''\n| Documentary\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''The Stowaway''\n| ''[[El pasajero clandestino]]''\n| Made for television\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1997\n| ''99.9''\n|  ''99.9''\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Sea (2000 film)|The Sea]]''\n| ''El Mar ''\n| Based on a novel by Blai Bonet.\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 2002\n| ''[[Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino|Aro Tolbukhin in the Mind of a Killer]]''\n| ''Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino ''\n| Co-directed with [[Lydia Zimmermann#Isaac Pierre Racine|Isaac Pierre Racine]] and [[Lydia Zimmermann]].\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''After the rain''\n| ''Despr\u00e9s de la pluja ''\n| Made for television\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Black Bread]]''\n| ''Pa Negre''\n|Winner of nine [[Goya Awards]], including best film, best director and best adapted screenplay.\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''A Letter to Evita''\n| ''Una carta para Evita ''\n| TV series, 2 episodes; [[Gaud\u00ed Awards|Gaud\u00ed Award]] 2014 for the best TV movie; at [[Biarritz International Festival of Audiovisual Programming]] 2013 two [[FIPA d'Or]] awards to [[Julieta Cardinali]] as the best actress and to Alfred P\u00e9rez, Roger Dan\u00e8s and Agust\u00ed Villaronga for the best script; at Monte-Carlo TV Festival 2013 Golden Nymph(s) to [[Julieta Cardinali]] for outstanding actress in a mini-series and to Teresa Enrich, Agust\u00ed Villaronga, Copia Cero Producciones, Radio Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola (RTVE), Televisi\u00f3 de Catalunya (TV3) for outstanding mini-series<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1967684/awards?ref_=tt_awd awards] at IMDb</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Uncertain Glory''\n| ''Incerta Gl\u00f2ria''\n| Based on the novel [[Uncertain Glory]] of [[Joan Sales]].\n|}\n\n== Other projects==\n* ''Anta mujer'' (1976) - Short\n* {{proper name|''Al mayurka''}} (1980) - Short\n* ''Laberint'' (1980) - Short\n* ''[[Fuck Them All]]'' (2005) - Music video for [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0898063|Agust\u00ed Villaronga}}\n\n{{Goya Award for Best Director}}\n{{Goya Award for Best Original Screenplay}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Villaronga, Agusti}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Director Goya Award winners]]\n[[Category:Catalan film directors]]\n[[Category:Catalan-language film directors]]\n[[Category:French-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT directors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Spain]]\n[[Category:LGBT screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Spain]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Mallorca]]\n[[Category:Spanish film directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language LGBT writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|Villaronga|Riutort}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Agust\u00edVillaronga.jpg\n| name         = Agust\u00ed Villaronga\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|03|04}}\n| birth_place  = [[Majorca]], Spain\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Film director, screenwriter, actor\n| yearsactive  = 1976\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Agust\u00ed Villaronga Riutort''' ({{IPA-ca|\u0259\u0263us\u02c8ti \u03b2i\u028e\u0259\u02c8\u027eo\u014b\u0261\u0259}}; born 4 March 1953)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/personne/fichepersonne_gen_cpersonne=202979.html|title=Agust\u00ed Villaronga|website=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|access-date=2 March 2016|language=fr}}</ref> is a Balearic Spanish [[film director]], [[screenwriter]] and actor.<ref name=\"spainisculture\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spainisculture.com/en/artistas_creadores/agusti_villaronga.html |title=Agust\u00ed Villaronga |accessdate=18 November 2011 |work=spainisculture}}</ref> He has directed seven feature films, a documentary, three projects for television and three shorts. His film ''[[Moon Child (1989 film)|El ni\u00f1o de la luna]]'' was entered into the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/237/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Moon Child |accessdate=1 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 he won the [[Goya Award for Best Director]] for ''[[Black Bread|Pa negre (Black Bread)]]''. The film was selected as the Spanish entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[84th Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"84th\">{{cite web |url=http://premiososcar2012.blogspot.com/2011/09/pa-negre-representara-espana-en-los.html |title=\"PA NEGRE\" REPRESENTAR\u00c1 A ESPA\u00d1A EN LOS OSCAR |accessdate=28 September 2011|work=CBC}}</ref> but it did not make the final shortlist.<ref name=\"Oscar Shortlist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2012/20120118.html |title=9 Foreign Language Films Vie for Oscar |accessdate=19 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67p5yGZlK?url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2012/20120118.html |archivedate=21 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nAgust\u00ed Villaronga was born on 4 March 1953 in [[Palma de Mallorca]], his grandparents had been itinerant puppeteers and his father was a child of the [[Spanish Civil War]], a fact that would resurface repeatedly in the director's filmography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2012/01/the-secret-of-black-bread-170412|title=The Secret of ''Black Bread''|last=Levine|first=Sydney|date=11 January 2012|website=[[IndieWire]]|access-date=7 July 2016|quote=Nor was [''Black Bread''] Villaronga's first film about children in the post Spanish Civil War era. [''The Sea''], ''In a Glass Cage'' and [''Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino''] all spoke of the consequences of the war, the perversions of war which changes the nautre of human beings, now, after, in the future and before. The perversions of war most interests Villaronga.}}</ref> Since childhood, his father encouraged his love for films and from early in his life he wanted to become a film director. He worked as an actor and made some shorts.\n\nVillaronga made his directorial debut in 1986 with the film ''[[Tras el cristal]]'', which was selected by the [[Berlin film festival]] receiving critical praise and many awards. The plot follows a former Nazi doctor, now paralyzed and depending on an iron lung to live, who begins to be taken care of by a young man, one of the children he abused during the war.\n''Tras el cristal'' already shows some of the key elements in Villaronga's filmography: a disturbed childhood marked by violence an early discovery of sexuality.\n\nHis second film, ''[[Moon Child (1989 film)|El ni\u00f1o de la Luna]]'' (1989), is about a child who goes to Africa to join a tribe awaiting the arrival of white child God. In 1992 he made a documentary, ''Al Andaluz'', produced by Segetel and the [[MoMa]] of [[New York city]]. For some years Villaronga tried unsuccessfully to find financing to adapt a novel by [[Merc\u00e8 Rodoreda]], ''Muerte en Primavera''. Instead he had to take some commission works. One of these was ''El pasajero clandestino'', a made for television project that lacked the personal characteristics of his filmography.\n\nCalled by actress [[Mar\u00eda Barranco]], Villaronga directed ''99.99'' a horror film more in synch with his themes, and that won some awards in festivals specialized in fantastic cinema. In 2000, Villaronga came back with a project of his own: ''[[The Sea (2000 film)|El mar]]'', a story set in [[Mallorca]] about three former childhood friends, traumatized by the violence they experienced during the Spanish civil war, that are reunited ten years later as young adults in a sanitary of tubercular patiences. The key elements in Villaronga's filmography are present in this story: childhood, sexual awakening, homosexuality and violence.\n\nIn 2002, Villaronga  co-directed with [[Lydia Zimmermann]] and [[Lydia Zimmermann#Isaac Pierre Racine|Isaac Pierre Racine]] the film ''[[Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino|En la mente del asesino]]''. In 2005 he directed a music video for French superstar [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]]'s song ''[[Fuck Them All]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mylene.net/mylene/c_fuck-them-all.php|title=Mylene.Net - Le site r\u00e9f\u00e9rence sur Myl\u00e8ne Farmer|author =Julien AUTIER|author2 =Philippe LEZE|author3 =Guillaume DATEZ|author4 =Sarah HOFER|last-author-amp =yes|work=mylene.net|accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> In 2007 he made ''Despu\u00e9s de la lluvia'', a made for television project adapting a stage play. It was only until 2010 with ''Pa negre'', when Villaronga finally achieved wider appeal. This film, winner of nine [[Goya Award]] including best film and best director, tells the story of an elven year old boy who growing up in the harsh period of the aftermath of the Spanish Civil War in [[Catalonia]]'s countryside discovers the world of lies around him.\n\nVillaronga followed ''P\u00e1 negre'''s success with  ''A Letter to Evita'', a TV miniseries co-produced by TV3, which recounts a real episode in the life of [[Eva Per\u00f3n]] while visiting [[Spain]] in the late 1940s.\n\nVillaronga is openly gay.<ref name=\"The Advocate, 11 April 2000, p. 46\">{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IGMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46 |title=Darkness in Berlin|accessdate=20 January 2013|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=11 April 2000|page=46}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography as director==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 99%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n!width=\"5%\"|Year\n!width=\"20%\"|English title\n!width=\"35%\"|Original title\n!width=\"40%\"|Notes\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Tras el cristal|In a Glass Cage]]''\n| ''Tras el cristal'' \n| Manfred Salzberg Award at the [[Berlin film festival]]\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1989\n| ''[[Moon Child (1989 film)|Moon Child]]''\n| ''El ni\u00f1o de la luna''\n| \n|-\n| 1992\n| ''Al-Andalus: The Art of Islamic Spain''\n| ''Al-Andalus''\n| Documentary\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''The Stowaway''\n| ''[[El pasajero clandestino]]''\n| Made for television\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1997\n| ''99.9''\n|  ''99.9''\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Sea (2000 film)|The Sea]]''\n| ''El Mar ''\n| Based on a novel by Blai Bonet.\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 2002\n| ''[[Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino|Aro Tolbukhin in the Mind of a Killer]]''\n| ''Aro Tolbukhin. En la mente del asesino ''\n| Co-directed with [[Lydia Zimmermann#Isaac Pierre Racine|Isaac Pierre Racine]] and [[Lydia Zimmermann]].\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''After the rain''\n| ''Despr\u00e9s de la pluja ''\n| Made for television\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Black Bread]]''\n| ''Pa Negre''\n|Winner of nine [[Goya Awards]], including best film, best director and best adapted screenplay.\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''A Letter to Evita''\n| ''Una carta para Evita ''\n| TV series, 2 episodes; [[Gaud\u00ed Awards|Gaud\u00ed Award]] 2014 for the best TV movie; at [[Biarritz International Festival of Audiovisual Programming]] 2013 two [[FIPA d'Or]] awards to [[Julieta Cardinali]] as the best actress and to Alfred P\u00e9rez, Roger Dan\u00e8s and Agust\u00ed Villaronga for the best script; at Monte-Carlo TV Festival 2013 Golden Nymph(s) to [[Julieta Cardinali]] for outstanding actress in a mini-series and to Teresa Enrich, Agust\u00ed Villaronga, Copia Cero Producciones, Radio Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola (RTVE), Televisi\u00f3 de Catalunya (TV3) for outstanding mini-series<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1967684/awards?ref_=tt_awd awards] at IMDb</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Uncertain Glory''\n| ''Incerta Gl\u00f2ria''\n| Based on the novel [[Uncertain Glory]] of [[Joan Sales]].\n|}\n\n== Other projects==\n* ''Anta mujer'' (1976) - Short\n* {{proper name|''Al mayurka''}} (1980) - Short\n* ''Laberint'' (1980) - Short\n* ''[[Fuck Them All]]'' (2005) - Music video for [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0898063|Agust\u00ed Villaronga}}\n\n{{Goya Award for Best Director}}\n{{Goya Award for Best Original Scr